SIMPLE: spunk
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spunk
<hw>Spunk</hw> <pr>(sp⟦ucr⟧⟦nsm⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gael.
<ets>spong</ets>, or Ir. <ets>sponc</ets>, tinder, sponge; cf. AS.
<ets>sponge</ets> a sponge (L. <ets>spongia</ets>), <ets>sp⟦omac⟧n</ets>
a chip. Cf. <er>Sponge</er>, <er>Punk</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>sponk</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Wood that readily takes
fire; touchwood; also, a kind of tinder made from a species of fungus;
punk; amadou.</def> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inflammable temper; spirit; mettle; pluck;
<as>as, a man of <ex>spunk</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lawless and dangerous set, men of <qex>spunk</qex>, and spirit,
and power, both of mind and body.</q> <rj><qau>Prof.
Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spunky</ent>⟦br⟧
